<br>
I think what Mike is trying to ask is how does obfuscate and security cameras work?  When can the character be seen and when can he not on the tape?<br>
<br>
All disciplines, unless otherwise stated, are line of sight only.  That means that you can only fool someone that could &quot;see&quot; you (even if they aren't actually &quot;seeing&quot; you due to obfuscate).  Therefore, a guard watching a monitor in a closed room where the hiding character can not see him sees the hiding character perfectly well.<br>
<br>
If the same guard were watching from a desk in the lobby that the character is sneaking through, the guard wouldn't notice anything amiss.<br>
<br>
Here's where it gets a little tricky...<br>
<br>
I *think* that obfuscate is retroactive.  The guard from the lobby didn't see the kindred in question on the first pass, but if, for some reason, he gets a chance to review the tape, he will see what he didn't the first time around (the obfuscating character).  HOWEVER, if the character is still with him (and hiding) when he is reviewing the tape, he is still hidden and/or masked on the tape.<br>
<br>
Strange stuff, no?<br>
<br>
As to when it's ok to check.  Darren has a good and reliable way.  If you set up a pattern of when you are looking for hidden people, no one can say anything when you check.<br>
<br>
I also make it a practice to use Auspex occasionally to check for snoops, sometimes even if no one else is around.<br>
<br>
~Chris <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hart@scbnforum58570>Hart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 2:53:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Rules Clarification - Obfuscate</span><hr size=1> Thank you Chris<br>
I vote for what Chris said.<br>
lol <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nesuril>Nesuril</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 3:19:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Obfuscation (John's Opinion)</span><hr size=1> In my mind, or from what I have gathered about this game, I generally handle obfuscate like this:<br>
<br>
Video or technological equipment defeats obfuscation period. A Nosferatu sneaking into the lobby of a building monitored by video cameras, would appear to a guard in another room as a horrid monster sneaking through the lobby, pretending like he/she is hidden. Others around her would not regard that creature at all, but someone in the same area watching a video camera would NOT see that person. For example a guard at the front desk would not see the Nosferatu sneak past him, even if he was looking at the camera. However, the Nosferatu sure as hell is on tape walking past. He does not fool the camera. Here's why:<br>
<br>
<b>When you obfuscate you are in a sense projecting a form of limited dominate onto a group around your presence. Constantly you are sending off little messages that say "Don't see me" ..."Don't see me". And most mortals don't see you, because their mind simply blocks you out.</b><br>
<br>
Now since a mechanical device cannot be dominated under "normal" levels of Obfuscation, it is never fooled by an Obfuscation invasion. Also, since a guard or observer not in the presence of the Nosferatu is not affected by the "Don't see me" message, he/she can see the Nosferatu just fine through the camera. Chris is right that basically Obfuscation is a "line of sight" power. Now, at Master level disciplines there are rumors that Obfuscate can affect machinery too. However, this is beyond the power of most neonates.<br>
<br>
Its the classic flaw of Vampire in the modern age: Technology can defeat the ancient powers of vampires quite easily in some cases. Guns, missles, computers, and other technologies are the bane of even the most powerful Elders. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=antoineleblanc@scbnforum58570>Antoine leblanc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 5:17:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Obfuscation </span><hr size=1> From Vampire The Masquerade pg 166 &quot;... such is Obfuscates ability to bend the mind that someone using a recording device will not see the immortals image until she views the footage at a later date, if even then.<br>
<br>
IMHO, letting people with cameras see through Obfuscate without tests takes away from gameplay.  If nothing else, they should be allowed tests with the stealth ability to avoid the cameras. <br>
<br>
<br>
Jacob         <br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nesuril>Nesuril</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 5:22:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Heh</span><hr size=1> It just forces the Nosferatu and other clans with obfuscate (Malkav, Samedi) to be more careful about where they go and what they do. Forces them to be more concious that they very well could violate the Masquerade by going into the wrong place and doing the wrong thing.<br>
<br>
I do agree they should get stealth checks and possibly security checks to disable/detect/avoid cameras. Its only fair. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stephencrowley>Stephen Crowley</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://lagoon.freebsd.lublin.pl/~fenix/smieci/graf/rozne/vampire/camarilla.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/21/03 5:38:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=20.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lagoon.freebsd.lublin.pl/~fenix/smieci/graf/rozne/vampire/camarilla.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Response</span><hr size=1> Wow, that's a lot of feedback.<br>
<br>
When I first started this game, I was told that film viewed in &quot;real time&quot; wouldn't pick up ob, because the person (not the machine) seeing the film in real time would be affected.      <br>
<br>
Assuming the ob'd character was going in to some place WORTH sneaking into, you've got to assume the security tapes would be reviewed at some point. At that point, they'd usually be spotted, with whatever consequences normally ensuing.  <br>
<br>
Nos, of course, would have a double-wammy. Not only would they be seen, but by their very appearance they are a walking Masquerade breach, even with Mask of 1000 Faces. <br>
<br>
There is a Merit in the Nos clan book that corrects that. Would it be applicable?<br>
<br>
